    "heading_text": "Stream JSON Lines with FastAPI",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/stream-json-lines/#stream-json-lines-with-fastapi",
    "chunk_index": 0,
    "chunk_text": "Stream JSON Lines with FastAPI. To stream JSON Lines with FastAPI you can, instead of using return in your path operation function , use yield to produce each item in turn. If each JSON item you want to send back is of type Item (a Pydantic model) and it's an async function, you can declare the return type as AsyncIterable[Item] : If you declare the return type, FastAPI will use it to validate the data, document it in OpenAPI, filter it, and serialize it using Pydantic.",
    "token_count": 126,
    "kind": null,
    "title": null
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tutorial/stream-json-lines::section-0006::chunk-0000",
    "chunk_kind": "heading",
    "source_node_id": "tutorial/stream-json-lines::section-0006",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/stream-json-lines::section-0005",
    "page_id": "tutorial/stream-json-lines",
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "level": 3,
    "heading_text": "Non-async path operation functions",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/stream-json-lines/#non-async-path-operation-functions",
    "chunk_index": 0,
    "chunk_text": "Non-async path operation functions. You can also use regular def functions (without async ), and use yield the same way. FastAPI will make sure it's run correctly so that it doesn't block the event loop. As in this case the function is not async, the right return type would be Iterable[Item] :",
    "token_count": 77,
    "kind": null,
    "title": null
  },
